text: This is possibly my favorite "fast food chain" per-say. Everything is amazing. Although sometimes the servers don't fill up the whole container of you ask for it to be on the side or is completely fresh, it never fails to taste amazing. It's almost as good as guacamole in Mexico, but definitely the best in Oregon. It isn't a thick or watery consistency with the perfect size and amount of avocado chunks which makes it perfect.

text: I have a job that sends me anywhere within a 50 mile radius of Portland, so it's just easier to eat out.  For the past week I've been in the Murray-Scholls area and have gone to this Chipotle about 3 times so far.  Every time I come in, there's this energetic woman that helps me with the first part of my order.  Totally off topic, but her voice kind of sounds like Rebel Wilson's and I find it really endearing.  Anyway, she's great, and she helped me again today, making sure I had fresh veggies instead of the ones that had been out for awhile.  When I got to the register it was a young lady with a massive amount of hair tied back in a bun (she gave me her name but I don't remember) and she was with another young gentleman, and they were both very pleasant.  I was fumbling around in my purse and realized I had forgot my debit card at home, and didn't have cash.  I was really embarrassed and felt bad, and after telling the girl at the register my mistake I turned to go...  Now this is why I went through the trouble of downloading this app, making a profile, and writing this review.  Instead of making it awkward, or just letting me continue on my way, she very sweetly and enthusiastically stopped me from leaving and offered for me to still have my order.  It's not just what they did (the guy was in on it too) but the way they made me feel so good about it.  It really made my day.  She said that if I wanted to leave a review that would be more than worth it, and I thought that was a great way to pay back the kindness.  Food-wise, this is just like any Chipotle, but the service really makes it stand out
name: Chipotle Mexican Grill

text: This Chipotle has become one of those places where the employees give intentionally poor service (especially as the evening goes on) in the hopes that you will go away. Funny, since Gusto! is basically next door & even has a sign out front that says "OUR CHIPOTLE IS BETTER," bc they have a bowl option that is incredibly similar. And their format is similar. Only it IS infinitely better, as is the service, & cleanliness. (It just costs more.) So I ended up here at 10 til close after never getting waited on at Tomatillos in East Atlanta, not intentionally showing up somewhere at the last minute. I came here bc I was starving and trying to save the $ I should've spent on Gusto! instead. I walked in & asked for a burrito bowl for here. (I always finish in under 10 minutes, as I did tonight.) The girl promptly listed off a BUNCH of ingredients they were "out of" (read: they decided to stop "making" it for the night; no way whoever does inventory didn't have all that stocked in the store to basically heat up & dump in a vat), in a tone that clearly conveyed her hope it would encourage me to turn around and exit in frustrated side-eyeing disappointment, rather than have her go through the effort of scooping ingredients into a bowl one more time (for, you know, her income/employment). I told her I was starving so I looked at what was left and figured out a way to still make myself a satisfying burrito bowl, albeit sans two of my usual ingredients (or lettuce - the "out of" included brown rice, corn, lettuce, and I think some meat option(s)). She looked disappointed but obliged, although she oddly had me repeat my choices of black beans and chicken. Then the cashier, instead of saying, "Anything else?" or "Anything to drink?" said, avoiding eye contact (chatting with the security guard), "That's all?" and started to tell me my total. So I had to say no and tell her what juice I wanted. Then she said, "That's all?" and rung me up, again with no eye contact. I went to sit and quickly eat my food, and the tops of almost every interior table were filthy. Which maybe explained why all but one customer was eating on the patio? I was going to photograph all of the nastiness, but just as I sat, the cashier started cleaning up - in order to leave sooner. At 5 minutes til close, she was loudly announcing to the security guard, in the dining area in the presence of me & another customer, to lock the door "at 10. Not 10:01, not 10:02. TEN." Yeah. I've worked at Starbucks and other such jobs. This is not how you are being paid to behave with or around customers. So I guess they'll enjoy their search for new employment soon when they succeed at stopping their customers from returning, and pushing us all over to Gusto!, where they will definitely never be hired. Oh - second star is only because the food was fine, the price is fine, parking lot, and I assume their health score was probably okay, but I could be wrong there. Oh, Willy's and another Mexican-style place are also within a stone's throw, next to Starbucks. I rec either of them or Gusto! instead, after about 5 1/2 years of coming here and watching it slide downhill.
name: Chipotle Mexican Grill

text:
Yes, this Chipotle has long lines, but I've seen longer lines at Chipotle locations towards the OTP suburbs.  Poncey-Highland Chipotle is located along a very busy stretch of Ponce, next door to Friends on Ponce, and across the street from Green's and Murder Kroger.  The clientele at this Chipotle is often young, hip, and urban.

The parking lot is small.  The restaurant acknowledges this with signs that say, words to the effect of: "Our burritos are big, but our parking lot is small."  It's not uncommon to see a panhandler directing traffic in the parking lot and asking for money later.  If you can't find parking, I suggest parallel parking along Maiden Ln. behind the restaurant.  I don't know how strict Friends and other neighboring businesses are with towing Chipotle customers, so be careful.

Compared to other locations, this Chipotle is relatively small.  It does have a nice enclosed and elevated patio which is a prime spot for people watching (traffic watching?) on Ponce.

I've generally found the food and service to be good, which is consistent with other locations.  Chipotle takes pride in its naturally raised meats, organic vegetables, and sustainable building practices.  Tastewise, I can't tell a significant difference between a burrito at Chipotle and a burrito at Moe's or Willy's -- they all taste good to me -- but it doesn't hurt to know that you're eating better stuff at Chipotle.

Burritos, burrito bowls, tacos, and salads range in price from $6.25 to $6.65 per order depending on the meat selection.  Meats include chicken, steak, carnitas, and barbacoa.  Cilantro-lime rice, black beans, pinto beans, salsa, cheese, sour cream, and other toppings are included.  Guacamole is $1.80 extra.  I'm a fan of the rice.

Like other burrito joints, Chipotle has a made-to-order, line ordering format.  You control what goes into your burrito from the very beginning.  The open kitchen is located behind the ordering counter, so you can see all the meats and other ingredients being prepared and cooked fresh.  During peak times, it's possible for the ordering line to run out of certain ingredients when it's your turn to order.

One of my favorite items to get is the burrito bowl because it's simple, tasty, and relatively healthy.  It's also easy to transport on-the-go.  I like to get chicken or steak.  All of the meats aren't bad.  The chicken is surprisingly tender.  I usually load my burrito bowls with all available toppings, particularly corn salsa and spicy salsa (in addition to the standard pico de gallo).  The spicy salsa is indeed spicy.  If that's not enough, hot sauce is available.

Drinks, condiments, and silverware are self-serve.  Satisfactory service.

Overall, not a bad in-town Chipotle.  Just wish the parking situation was better.

text:
I'll admit it: I was a hater. 

I hadn't ever set foot in a Chipotle until late last year in NYC.  It didn't appeal to me on any level. I don't eat fast food. I don't like the mention of McDonald's within 500 feet of my person.

Despite not having tried it, I found it easy to mock the people going in there, to sneer at the faux-Mexican food, and to insist that it never enter my intestines, no matter who vouched for it.

My ever-awesome boyfriend had a sit down with me.  He looked me straight in the eye [I only have one] and said, "just try it.  If you don't like it, I'll never, ever mention it again."  He wasn't arguing for its culinary superiority or authenticity, just that it's flavorful, usually fresh, cheap, and most importantly, reliable.

17 barbacoa tacos, 5 black bean burritos and a chicken burrito bowl later, I couldn't agree more.

No, it's not real Mexican.  But it's damn tasty.  Food doesn't necessarily have to be authentic to a particular remote region of the world to taste good. There's lots of variations in between.  If you want real Mexican or real Latin food, I would never suggest coming here. There's really no point in making those comparisons. There's a grand distinction between pretty fresh fast food and a slow cooked, authentic sit down dinner. Apples and oranges, man.  

If you want something easy, tasty, and not devastating to your colon and wallet, it's a fine way to go.  In the fast food/convenience department, they do set themselves apart from the greasy, tasteless rest.

And since my office is just down the street in Inman Park, right next to the Beltline (which I walk frequently at lunch), it was an easy decision to hop off the Beltline one day and walk over to Chipotle to pick up lunch.

Unlike the Chipotle that's closest to my home, this Chipotle's crew was on point for lunch! I was honestly in and out in five minutes flat - this literally, never happens. Even though there were three other people in front of me in line, and it was peak lunch hour, as soon as I stepped up to the counter I was greeted and moved down the line in the most efficient way I've ever seen. It was really, really impressive. 

Plus, my burrito bowl was perfect, as usual. Good job, Chipotle. If your store is this efficient all the time, I will definitely be back.

text:
Chipotle is the first of their kind to do clean food as they do. 
When is comes to their free range animals, local ingredients, and vegan options Chipotle has no competition. 
I often hear people criticizing Chipotle for being a 'chain' establishment when rather they should be applauded for their organic standards which should be held as a role model to other businesses.
Never lack of flavor in any of their ingredients, raw industrial motif, and completely fair prices is what keeps my respects for Chipotle steep and is what has me constantly returning.
As for the customer service its an easy 3 stars. I have been to multiple Chipotle's throughout the U.S including Texas, Kentucky, Florida, and now Georgia and the employes have either been decent or completely horrible. Very disappointing for, in my opinion, their almost flawless establishment. 
Very glad to see that they have always acquired their liquor license, its always great to grab a beer or margarita with Mexican food.
My only recommendation would be more appealing margarita cups and a larger selection of beers. 
I hope Chipotle keeps up their unconventional standards in comparison to other businesses and over all continues to crush the Mexican grilled food.

text:
If I could give this location NO STARS I WOULD! I'm a Chipotle fan but this location is by far THE WORST!

The staff there has the most horrendous attitudes. Talking while there are customers WAITING . The location is always unkept and not properly stocked. The food isn't properly handled.

Today I stopped to pick up a burrito bowl. This location clearly prefers to hire teenagers to work behind the counter . They are not very professional.  As I tell the  2nd young lady  who puts on the salsa etc what I would like we come to the corn salsa which is clearly low. I request two scoops as Inalways do, she barely gave me 1 scoop and said with with a smart tone that's all there is. That's it . I looked at her and asked I would like more. She just looked at me . I please pack up my order it seems you have an attitude. She rolled her eyes and laughed. 

As I go to the checkout to pay I see a card but it wasn't for the owner of the location so I asked the young lady ringing me up for the information. She says she didn't know but the supervisor was there . A guy comes over states he is the supervisor and his name is Don. 
I asked for the locations owner /manager. He says what is the problem. I state I would prefer to speak with the owner/manager. He stays he isn't ABLE  to give me the information. I restate what he has told me and then I say if he is refusing to give me said persons contact information, I will contact Corporate. Don states I guess you will need to do that.

I take my food, I go over to the counter with napkins cutlery to put in my bag as I'm. STILL in the location. (By the way it is terribly unkept or stocked. I state on my way out, you should've waited until  I left the store before discussing it and furthermore you should not be discussing it on the FLOOR in front of other customers because it is Unprofessional!

Needless to say, I will not return and I have sent this to Corporate as well. I will return if I hear from them or not.

text: There aren't many Chipotle locations in the Atlanta area, so this one doesn't have much competition. They have some parking, but not enough. I ordered (and paid) online ahead so I could run in and pick up my food. I arrived at the time they said it would be ready (3:45 pm - not a rush time), and they hadn't even started making it. There were only 2 people in line. Everyone there when I showed up plus many more customers made it through the line and paid for their food before I could get mine. The whole point of ordering online is timeliness and predictability, which were completely defeated. Lesson: don't online order. Show up and wait with everyone else if you must visit this location. Once they started to make my order, they needed to replace half of the ingredients in the line, which made making my (already late) order take much longer than it should have. I can't imagine what they do during the lunch rush. Ingredients were fine - I think the Sofrito tastes just like chili, so if you don't like chili (like the soup) then skip it. I appreciate the vegan option (other than veggie) though. Their salad dressing containers are sadly not even half full and I had to request the dressing with my salad.

text:
I go here probably 3 or 4 times a month. The parking lot situation is hellish. It's a war zone. The line almost always has 9 or more people in front of you and moves slowly. Lately they are always very backed up. As in 6 half-made orders just lying next to each other waiting to be finished and people in line just waiting all cramped together. And usually one of the people on the food line doubles as the cashier. There used to be a really nice guy at the register... I miss him. A lot of the people there now are rude and don't look at or respond to you.

Order a salad, they give you about a cup of lettuce. Ask for rice, they give you less than a cup. The meat portions are upsetting. Today I got no more than 4 Tablespoons of chicken. What the hell? They also gave me about 3 tablespoons of beans because the container was running low and I guess she didn't want to go get more. Ask for more meat and you pay double for a normal portion size. Today I only got chicken in every 5th or 6th bite. The food here is blander than other chipotles. I have to add salt. 

A few months ago, there was a girl training another girl on the line. It was a terrible time for it because it was busy. I asked for guacamole and the girl being trained gave me about a quarter of the regular amount of guacamole. I asked if I could have a little more and she gave me a little more, still not enough. Whatever. I'm being rung up and the girl who was training the new chick suddenly stops what she's doing to yell over to the guy at the register that I got double guac, without looking at or speaking to me. Luckily it was too late. My receipt was printing out, but that was so odd because she watched the girl give me an extremely small amount of guac when they usually give you a mountain. And she was angry, as if I had gotten away with something. I'm finally giving up on this location. There's a very nice one on Peachtree. Friendly with regular portion sizes.
name: Chipotle Mexican Grill

text:
Ordered from these guys on doordash...

They were out of chorizo. Doordash called and explained, so my response was "no problem, how about steak?"

Chipotle manager: "steak is 50 cents more and the order was prepaid, so can't do."

For more background, chorizo is 55 cents more than a standard meat option and steak is 1.05 more. Most reasonable people at this point would have just put steak in the bowl.

Ok, fine - seems a bit ridiculous, but fine. How about chicken... how about no meat at all (that was the only option I was given as an alternative even though I paid extra for a premium option that they were out of and never updated on the app - not even a downgrade to a standard option). Got a bowl with beans and cheese. So... they are okay with taking money from me and not giving me what I paid for in return.

Used to eat here twice a week. Never again. Absolutely s$&@ service. It's not that hard to be a manager at chipotles but this a&&hole apparently can't figure it out. Idiots.

I ultimately went through the app to get a full refund that will be charged back to the merchant, so brilliant work manager - mission not accomplished at all.

text:
Chipotle as a brand gets about 789 stars from me, but this location specifically is consistently frustrating to visit. This location is the closest one to me, but I will typically go out of the way to a different store to avoid this one.

I've given it about 6 chances, and each time I am disappointed. Somehow, there are always an excess of employees, but the service is usually very slow. They are almost always out of something major (like cheese or guac, or last night both cheese AND guac lol). I am genuinely worried for these employees because they are typically so unenthused that I wonder if they've all recently been screamed at.

The food assembly line is all messy and sloppily scooped, so there's always corn in the sour cream, barbacoa in the chicken, etc....

And finally, somehow, the very corporate recipes taste a little different at this location. One thing I love about Chipotle is that you can expect consistency whether you're in Cleveland, OH,  Atlanta, GA or anywhere in between. Somehow this location always tastes just a little bit different. Specifically the seasoning on the peppers and on the chicken.

text:
Prior to the Midtown location opening, this used to be my Chipotle location of choice. It has all the usual fixings you'd expect at a Chipotle, but let's break it down:

PARKING: World's smallest parking lot. It will be a challenge to find a spot during primetime hours but I've always managed to find one eventually. There's also street parking available right behind the restaurant on one of the side streets, so it's not too terrible to drive here.

FOOD: My experience here with the food is usually pretty good, definitely what you'd expect from a Chipotle. No complaints about the quality or taste.

ATMOSPHERE: Again, pretty typical for Chipotle. More space inside than you'd think based on the size of the parking lot. It's also usually pretty clean in here in the dining area, and the condiments station is typically well-stocked and I've never had to hunt down a plastic fork or napkins from the cashier.

SERVICE: This is where I dropped my rating a couple stars. Having worked at a quick service restaurant for almost 6 years, I have a pretty solid understanding of how they should be run. This location is always hit or miss. For example, tonight's experience -- one of the younger employees had his AirPods in while working the food line this evening. As you'd expect, this did not go well since he's required to hear what a customer is saying as part of his job. While he was putting my burrito together I asked for "regular steak" (instead of the new carne asada) and then watched as he piled my tortilla high with chicken. I then told him I asked for steak and he said, "No, you said chicken." I corrected him and said, "No, I asked for regular steak." Without saying another word, he smirked and remade my burrito. Annoying, but whatever. Then... I hate sour cream, so I don't ever get it on my burritos. Unfortunately, there was a huge mess of sour cream globbed onto the food counter. While Air Pod Kid was wrapping my burrito, he pushed one end of the shell all up in this nasty mess of sour cream just sitting on the counter. Thankfully, another employee saw what he was doing and made him wrap it with different aluminum foil (since that, too, was covered in sour cream). I was reluctant to ask them to remake my burrito a THIRD time, so now I'm stuck with a burrito I don't really want because it's a mess of old ingredients I don't enjoy.

By the time we left, Air Pod Kid had taken the pods out of his ears, presumably because the experiment of working with them in was a disaster for me and it was obvious to his fellow staff members. Not super psyched that I was the guinea pig for that experiment, nor should a kid that arrogant and lazy be customer-facing.

Will I let it stop be from coming back to this location? Probably not. Chipotle is Chipotle. This location just needs to up its standards for staffing, especially because the one in Midtown has an AWESOME, super friendly staff that puts this location to shame.
name: Chipotle Mexican Grill

text:
My wife and I had a little bit of time before an appointment nearby and we were feeling a bit hungry and decided to make it a quick one.  So we decided to go to the nearest Chipotle. We entered and there was a line.  That didn't bother me because I expected it to be one being in downtown.

However, the line was not moving and only a few people were getting served.  I got to the counter and said that I wanted a chicken burrito.  The told me that they were out of chicken and beef.  Sorta sad situation since those are most likely the popular choices. There would be a seven to eight minute wait.  So my wife and I joined the line of waiting customers. 

I heard the manager, who was sitting with some corporate big wigs, to tell the crowd something and then we were told that our meal was comped due to waiting.  I think it was not the manager's idea to do this and was more forced by his company at the table.

Either way we got two free meals and drinks.  I had the burrito and the wife had the bowl.  I usually don't get guacamole due to the extra cost, but not this time, that shit was free. So when I was asked for guac I said, "Yes, please!."

My wife's bowl was good, however, my burrito was a leaky mess.  The bottom looked like it was taking a dump of beans into my basket.  Not appetizing. I had to open it up and finish it with a fork.

I didn't complain because it was free, but might have if I had to pay for it.  It was just unacceptable.
name: Chipotle Mexican Grill

text: I come to this Chipotle often, but the last few times I've visited, the service and quality have been quite sub-par, today's being the worst. When I arrived at approximately 5:20PM there were only a few people in the place so I expected that the attentiveness and quality would have been better. I ordered a burrito to go with half brown rice and half white rice with steak & sofritas with a side of chips. The portions of rice and meat I received were stingy and made me frown. I was haphazardly handed off to another employee to proceeded to be equally stingy with cheese and salsa. The burrito was then wrapped so poorly that it fell apart before I had a chance to unwrap it (by peeling the foil off of one end while keeping the rest of it wrapped like you're supposed to). I discovered that the rice was undercooked and grainy, the steak was overcooked, and the sofritas were cold (Note I only live a block away). To really drive the nail in the coffin on my meal, the chips were all stale. Now, I used to be a kitchen manager for Chipotle before I moved here from Ohio, so I know what the consistency and quality SHOULD be. This meal really missed the mark, and so did the attentiveness of the line employees. I WANT to love to go there often. There are so many other good burrito places in the neighborhood though that if the consistency is slipping this much, I might just begin going elsewhere. PLEASE train your employees better. I love Chipotle, and I want to continue to do so.
name: Chipotle Mexican Grill

text:

This place still has that "new burrito smell" since it recently opened, and I really hope they continue to focus on super service. It makes it really easy to NOT walk down the street to Taco Del Mar when you know you'll get greeted with a smile here.

Kudos to you and your team, and welcome to the 'hood!

text:
We've lived out here almost 10 years now, and I didn't visit a Chipotle until 2009.  This saddens me, b/c it is my favorite Mexican fast food establishment.  This particular Chipotle was very clean and not as empty on a Wednesday afternoon @ 2:30pm as one would expect.  The people working the counter were extra perky and very nice.

One of the things I love about Chipotle (besides the easy beanless options) is the portions.  They are usually huge and I feel like I've overeaten almost every time.  This was no exception.  Giant fajita carnitas burrito w/guacamole.  It made my afternoon so much more productive.

Parking was a breeze, but I'm definitely not going to guarantee that every time as it's in the Pearl.  So stop on by.  It's quick and filling.
name: Chipotle Mexican Grill

text:
I love Chipotle's food, and it's one of the best ways to get a healthy meal quickly in my opinion.  So that's great about this place.  

This location, however, is sometimes a bit spotty on service and speed. text:
I had such a great experience at Chipotle that I feel I must write a review! From time to time, I take my 3 kids there for dinner. Chipotle is always friendly, and very accomodating and flexible as far as making my kids' burritos/tacos/etc just the way they want them. We are not big fast food consumers, but Chipotle has me thinking this is a somewhat healthier alternative, so I feel OK about feeding this to my kids on occasion. 

This particular evening, one of my kids (spice wimp) ordered a chicken burrito, against my better judgment since I know there is some kick to the chicken. Not surprisingly, it was too spicey for him... when I went to order a carnitas version to replace it, on my nickel, Chipotle insisted on comping it, guacamole and all. I thought this was above and beyond as far as customer service. Additionally, at least two staff personnel came to check on us to see if the second burrito was more to his liking, and to make sure everyone else was doing well. 

Chipotle can feel on the pricey side, especially for extras like guacamole, but their portions are generous, the food is good quality, the service is great, and we will keep coming back.
name: Chipotle Mexican Grill

text:
I rarely review fast food (or whatever Chipotle is - the next step up?) because it is what it is.  It's food.  When I do, it's because it's really bad or really good.  In this case, it's really good.  Not all Chipotles, mind you (the one downtown isn't so wonderful), just this one.

The big thing Chipotle has going for it is that it actually is food (earlier I said fast food is just food, but that's not really true - it's not food, it's chemicals).  This location is also good at what it does.  They're friendly, efficient, they throw things together well . . . I suppose there was that one time that someone wasn't the best.

I'm not wanting to hand out my first five-star review to Chipotle, though.  It doesn't seem right.  I'm trying to think of something bad about them.  They . . . no.  They definitely . . . no.  Oh well.  I guess I have no choice.

text:
Like a moth to a flame, I manage to find my way to a Chipotle no matter what city I find myself in. 

Yes this is a chain, but at least I know what to expect. It is a fast, cheap, and safe gluten free dining option. A pretty hard combination to find at times, especially after working late at the office and not wanting to stray far from the hotel for a meal.

The design of this location is pretty good from others that I have seen in my travels. I do like how they a sectioned off the line and created a separated queue from the seating area. The seating area itself has a decent amount of tables.

As for the food, it is the standard fare. The taste of some of the ingredients seems to taste a bit off from what I am used to in other locations of the US. The steak and rice tends to seem a bit bland at times. 

The workers are good about changing their gloves when I alert them of my gluten allergy. They do have a process of changing out the line spoons, which seems to be a Portland protocol as I haven't seen this done anywhere else in my travels. I do have to give the staff credit for their knowledge on gluten and cross contamination as they do try to take extra precautions to eliminate the risks.

Overall, Chipotle is a good cheap GF dining option.
name: Chipotle Mexican Grill

text:
I regularly eat food from Chipotle and I love the food. At least one or twice a week I come in to order food or order online, so I have visited many restaurant locations. This is by far the WORST quality location I have yet to go to. 

I have been to this location at least 30+ times over the past year. Every time I come in the staff has been rude and they either take forever to make your food or rush you through the line rolling their eyes if you ask for anything more then what they give you. Other staff quickly apologized for their colleagues attitudes and frequently will offer "free" drinks/chips/guac to make up for other employees mistakes. Don't even get me started on the arguments and personal life drama conversations that happen. Where is management when they need it? No one knows.

I have never been to this location and been satisfied with a burrito. 90% of the time they are out of at least one or two ingredients because they have not been made and then you have to wait 15mins if you want them, making other customers wait longer in line. 50% of the time the rice you get has not been mixed well and you end up with a mouth full of salt. Additionally the guac is almost always brown and the queso is cold. My online orders have been wrong every time- you would think it would be simpler looking off a online order form to make a bowl. 

To wrap it up, tonight I stood in a line for over 25mins that in any other location would have taken less then 10mins. Also forget being sanitary- the staff filling up the food trays wasn't wearing gloves after stating mins before that he was going to the restroom. I even found a hair in my food tonight. 
The only reason I have continued to visit this location is per convince - however driving to another location seems like the better option at this point. I am fed up with waiting around to deal with rude staff that can't even make my burrito taste like it should.
name: Chipotle Mexican Grill
Ambience: {'romantic': False, 'intimate': False, 'touristy': False, 'hipster': False, 'divey': False, 'classy': False, 'trendy': False, 'upscale': False, 'casual': True}

text:
This really is the worst chipotle around. The inside is quite small and the partaking is horribly laid out with limited parking spaces. Not necessarily their fault but it certainly doesn't help. 

They are always backed up on orders so never expect your pick up order to be ready anywhere near on time. Especially around dinner time. I don't know why this particular chipotle is always so behind when others seem to manage this system just fine. My most recent visit consisted of standing around with 10+ other customers waiting on pick up orders... 

I know they get slammed and are moving as fast as they can, but this is not a one off experience and they really need to re-evaluate how they can make this process roll more smoothly. Perhaps the app should not suggest a pick up time that the restaurant cannot meet. I just want a clearer expectation of how long I might be waiting. 

The food, however, is pretty on par with typical chipotle so at least there's that. Though last time we had it delivered from this store, our order was no where near correct. If you can get to another Chipotle, do it. The one on Bethel is much better!

text:
Quick, filling, and tasty! Chipotle is my go-to destination when I need lunch or dinner but don't have time for (or don't want) the sit-down restaurant experience. The sofritas burrito is my all time favorite. It's spicing is phenomenal and it always hits the spot when I'm in a burrito mood.

I like this location because it's always fast and the interior has plenty of seating. The staff is always friendly, too. My only complaint is that sometimes the sofritas is a little dry. 

OH! If you're planning to order Chipotle here (or anywhere else for that matter) I HIGHLY recommend using the mobile app! You can customize your order and pay for it online. All you have to do when you arrive is walk to the counter to pick it up and you're on your way. It's SUPER convenient.

text:
Alright: Louisville Chiptole

This one has a special place in my heart; most Chipotles I've been to lack one thing: parking. Usually put in high-volume areas, they almost always lack that special something...easy access. This one however, as much parking as needed, and to boot, is never packed. I've always been able to get a good place to sit here, and the vaulted ceilings definitely help with the spacious feel of this Chipotle. The food has always been excellent and fresh, and the chips - always a hit and miss with Chipotle - have always been perfectly salted with lime. Seriously...you Denver people might think about making the drive, I'm telling you.

text:
Is this place even managed? I frequent chipotle at least three times a week and as much as I try to avoid this place I have ended up here a few times in the last two months. They are never open at 10:45 AM. Often times I am standing out the door waiting for them to open up as a few minutes goes by. When they do finally let me in there is no apology or reasoning for why they left me outside waiting for them to open. Even when I am inside I'm still waiting for them to hastily put the product in the right place. Often times the rice is from the night before and is still cold and hard. The trash cans are even full from the night before.

Today was my final straw. I was in a time crunch and I waited five minutes past the opening time which made me late for an appointment. On my way out I ran into the bathroom to wash my hands and there was no soap. The alarming factor was that the bathroom smelled like somebody went number two and I was the only customer in the store. This leads me to believe that one of the workers used the bathroom and did not wash his hands.  

I'm done.

text: I love Chipotle, but the food isn't always consistent at this location (nor is it anywhere else, but it's still worth noting at this one in particular). For the 2nd visit in a row, I've watched 2 different employees dump the black beans onto my burrito without draining them first! Having a soggy burrito dripping with bean juice is not my idea of quality. Another issue I have is that the chips are often prepared rather poorly. During my past few visits, I've gotten bags of chips that aren't fully fried! The softness and sogginess of the chips isn't helped by the overload of salt that they've drowned the chips in after prematurely pulling them from the fryer. Also, not to sound like a silly racist, but where have all the Mexicans gone that used to work at this location? Perhaps I've just gone when they aren't on shift. As far as I could tell, the food quality was always above average when it wasn't all white people working there (again, not to sound like a pathetic race-obsessed honky. I know this is Louisville). Overall I really can't complain, but just be weary when ordering chips! Make Chipotle Mexican Again!
name: Chipotle Mexican Grill

text:
I used to have a group of friends who were addicted to this place. 
They would literally get the shakes after 3 days without a Chipotle hit. Okay not the shakes, but they'd whine about why we were at *insert delicious restaurant* instead of The 'Potle. Yes, they call it that.

I didn't really get it.
Okay so the herbs that are chopped into the rice make it a bit more complex. They'd always request extra rice when ordering.
And the chicken is Bell & Evans. This is a very good organic chicken brand that you find at Whole Foods.
If I'm going to eat chicken here, I order it in the salad. 

Chipotle salads are good. It's gotta be the corn, cheese and warm black beans; the chipotle dressing is sweet and good too, but the salad doesn't really need it. Unfortunately the only lettuce in the salad is romaine. Dull.

A little known fact courtesy of the addicts is that you can order a quesadilla "off" the menu. It's something ridiculous like $3. I order it with Barbacoa. This is the shredded pork. They take two of the big flour tortillas, cover one with lots of cheese and meat, smack them together, and put them on a panini press of sorts. It's really delicious until you get about 80% done and realize the rest of the quesadilla (which has been wrapped up in foil for neatness-sake) is entirely soaked with grease, grease is dripping onto your plate at an alarming rate, and you're going to have a coronary at the ripe age of 40.
name: Chipotle Mexican Grill

text: I have been going here since I moved to atlanta about 5 years ago.  It used to be great, the people who worked there were great, their portions were satisfying, and food was seasoned and cooked well.  Sometime within the last year, or perhaps a little longer, things have gone south.  They now give you very small portions and are very rude if you ask for more.  They will actually give you a few pieces of meat and if you ask for more they tell you it's an extra 3 dollars.  Not only are portions small, but people are very rude if you ask for anything at all. They skimp on seasoning too and their meat is often dry, overcooked, and flavorless.  Don't go to this location, it is not a good or true chipotle experience.  Try the one in perimeter mall, or the one in sandy springs on roswell road.  This place is a waste of money and an overall bad chipotle experience. *written by a true chipotle lover who would eat there 2 or 3 times a day if given a choice.

text:
Jerry T.'s review is so on point that I scarcely have anything else to add. If you've been to Chipotle, then this one will neither displease nor impress you. I've been to this location countless times and while I've been annoyed during weekday lunch rush (which can be horrendous, what with all the office parks in the area), the food and service have been consistent.

I used to devour huge burritos but have persuaded myself that I can save the 300+ calories by forgoing the tortilla, so in recent times I've chosen the burrito bowls. Quite fresh ingredients, especially considering that this joint is still part of a fast food chain. My go-to protein is the barbacoa, which is wonderfully seasoned shredded beef. Rice and black beans always make an appearance and have not disappointed yet.

While it slightly peeves me that chips are not included, when compared to other burrito places, Chipotle's chips come out on top. And that pricy guacamole is pretty damn tasty.
name: Chipotle Mexican Grill

text:
Who's a big gurl Chipotle lover?  Me!  Until tonight...  I guess when you experience great food and service, you come to expect it at every location, but my experience at the Perimeter location tonight was not that great.

They had two new guys (I guess?) working.  The "rice and beans" guy was scraping the bottom of the rice pan when I walked up and asked for a burrito bowl.  He lifted the steamer machine thingy and started to put the paper bowl in, then realized what he was doing.  Instead of getting a new pan of rice, he managed to scrape up about 1 and 1/4 spoons of rice and squish it in the bottom of my bowl.  Then, "rice and beans" guy said "Beans?", and I said, "Yeah...black beans" to which he reached into the vat of frijoles goodness and got one meager scoop of beans laden with "juice" and plopped it on top of the rice.

(mind you, by this time a seasoned employee had replaced the rice with a fresh batch and taken over rice station; I kept hoping "rice and beans" guy would put the bowl down and let someone else take over my bowl's assembly so that I might get a little more rice and bean goodness, minus the bean juice...but I digress).

By this time, "rice and beans" guy was giving me the tour of the "meat station".  I asked for chicken, and you guessed it, times are tough I guess so I got about half a spoon full of "pollo".  "Rice and beans" guy stopped at protein station, and his friend (who apparently was also new) at "toppings" station took over my predicament bowl, I MEAN burrito bowl.

"Toppings" guy asked what I wanted (yeah...) and I said "Green tomatillo please", to which he dropped the spoon and pulled out, oh, about an ounce of salsa (SCHERIOUSLY?), then a big ol' helping of sour cream, and a mountain of cheese.

I also noticed both garbage cans running over when I left, and a health inspection rating of 86.  No bueno.
name: Chipotle Mexican Grill

text:
It is amazing how much Chipotle quality can vary by location. This is easily the worst Chipotle I have ever visited. Unfortunately, I come here occasionally because it is the closest Chipotle to where I live.

The workers are not exactly rude, but you can tell they're miserable. Probably poor management. Every single time I come here they try to skimp you on portions, and - without fail - one of the key ingredients of my meal is scraped from the bottom of the pan. Cold night and line out the door? Of course the workers are sitting around eating their dinners during the dinner rush. That's not their fault, they're hungry. I spent years working in the food service industry - that's bad management.

This Chipotle should be shut down and reopened with better management. As much as I hate to write one star reviews, and as odd as it feels to write such a critical review of a chain, this place deserves it.

I am normally a banner-waving Chipotle fanatic. I hear they opened up one across the street in the Perimeter Mall - I recommend you head there instead. Oh yeah, and the parking is awful too.

text:
So I came here per the Oprah-factor. They featured this rest't as doing a great job in revolutionizing the fast food industry. the owner was on there talking about how he used to be an executive chef and he envisioned his rest'ts serving tasty, organic, and grass-fed meat. I think he's achieved 2/3: organic and grass-fed yay...but tasty, I can't give him that one. 
I ordered 3 soft tacos, each w/ a difft meat (chicken, pork, and beef) and topped it off w/ their hot salsa. text:
After living nearby for 4 years, I've been to this Chipotle more times than I can possibly count. I have to ask for at least two scoops of almost everything because they refuse to give you a normal amount of food. Chipotle isn't cheap. Give me some damn food.

Then there is the cleanliness issue. They do get very, very busy; but if they know that, hire someone full time to maintain the restaurant. Food on every table and don't even get me started on the floors. So gross.

If it wasn't for the consistent food taste and quality we'd just go to Willy's every time (although I cringe using that as a comparison bc they are completely different). But the truth is, when we don't feel like dealing with the hassle of this chipotle, we go to Willy's.

Oh I almost forgot, the new Chipotle that opened in Perimeter mall is a nice alternative if you don't mind parking/mall food court/etc.

text:
I have never written a review before, but am a very frequent diner at Chipotle, and today's experience was the final straw. I, and many people I know, love the food but we all constantly complain about the service. I definitely think it is certain locations, and this Dunwoody one is the WORST. I asked for a bowl today and wanted brown rice, but the woman making the bowl said they didn't have any. I asked her "are they just making it, or you don't have any at all?" She said "We only have white rice." I said "Are you sure?" She said "Yes." They make my bowl. As I am about to pay, they bring brown rice out.

Excuse me? You just told me you didn't have any brown rice. As in....at all. And do not tell me there is a language barrier. You understood what I said. I told the lady who was closing up the bowl, and she had them make me one with brown rice. Ok fine. But whoever the manager or owner is at this location, you must understand that this makes your entire operation look terrible. This is not the first time it has happened either. There is always something. Either they give you 3 pieces of meat, or sigh if you ask for one shred more lettuce. Most of them look like they hate being there, and that somehow, it's your fault. I am a huge customer service advocate, and this is honestly one of the worst places to go if you are looking for a pleasant experience.

There are many other restaurants that serve the same food. You need to realize your customers have that choice. Unfortunately, I will likely be choosing Willy's or Barberitos or even the Chipotle on Roswell Road in the future...I just cannot stand the service at this place. At Willy's they ask you how you're doing, they smile, they give you normal servings....they are more than amenable to the customer. They have just as long of a line and just as much pressure to keep it moving. But they are always a pleasure. Barberitos is not as overly friendly but they don't look like they want to strangle you at least, and their servings are pretty decent as well.

Someone in management should really do something about the service at this location.

I will not go back to this chipotle location ever again and you shouldn't either.

text:
This is the Chipotle location that turned me against the entire chain.  I will never visit another Chipotle because of my experiences at this one.

This location seems to employ the stupidest people in the entire Atlanta Metro.  Not only are they hard of hearing, they also don't understand clear, concise and simple English.

The vast majority of the stupidity lies in the person "in the middle" that handles the salsa, cheese and other toppings.  I have never in my life had so much difficulty getting through to a set of human beings in my life.  The first person usually gets it all right, which type of rice and beans.  Simple enough.  The cashier doesn't usually make too many errors, although on a number of occasions, they were unable to understand what, "I have double chicken," actually meant.  So, I made off with a little discount.  It was comical to see the shrugs from the other patrons in line so as to say, " They can't understand you, just take the free chicken."

The ultimate gripe here is that the pico de gallo is frequently on the ripe/rotten side and the chicken quality is trash.  Seriously, as disgusting as Pollo Tropical is in Georgia (versus Florida) their food is still five times better than this slop.

When sending my complaint to the corporate office over the rotten smell of the pico de gallo, I receive the defiant response from the store (via the corporate office) that the pico de gallo was freshly made just two hours prior.  Yeah right.  Was it left out in the open for those two hours?  Fresh tomatoes and onions do not develop a rotten smell in just two hours if stored properly.  Food safety is not a joke.

All in all, I see this location has an abysmal rating of 2.5 stars; they deserve it.
name: Chipotle Mexican Grill

I won't lie, since the whole scandal with Chipotle, I haven't been in quite some time; however, my wife swears by this place, so I gave it a try again. I've been to this location prior for a "BOGO" burrito bowl deal.

Overall, the experience at this Chipotle was good. I appreciate them for providing good service.

text:
Watching calories can be done, and Chipotle is one of my favorite places to dine when I want to feel full but avoid a calorie binge.
I choose the bowl and ditch the tortilla.  This is my bowl:
-Rice
-Black Beans (I ask for a little more beans and skip the onions/pepper blend and corn relish)
-Pico and a little of the medium hot sauce
-Cheese
-Guacamole
-Lettuce
Voila... a large amount of food for around 600 calories.  
I've never had problems with the employees at this location... partly because I anticipate the next question and SMILE when ordering.  The smile is usually returned and they throw on some more lettuce because they think i'm a vegetarian a friend to bovines.  This seems to be the case at all locations... but i'm also not a demanding guest looking for a long term relationship.   
I'd make the rice at home if I could find a comparable recipe.  Anyone have one?
name: Chipotle Mexican Grill

text:
I stepped on the scale this morning and lost three pounds. You know what that means? I am compelled to sabotage it with a trip to an eatery where I can order up 1,000 calories in one meal. I'm talking about big-hunking burritos. I'm talking Chipotle.

I am normally not a fan of Chipotle. Of all the big-hunking burrito chains, this one ranks pretty low on my list already for several reasons I won't get into here. But mainly, they just do not offer a big enough variety for my taste.

However, as it turns out today I was running an errand at the Arbor Walk and decided to buy my lunch at this Chipotle location. I figured since I ran 4 miles this morning and was heading to the office for who knows how long on a friggin Sunday, I should get something substantial to tide me over until my dinner of, most likely, beer while laying on the couch watching the Olympics. (Honestly, I really think I'm going to keep off that three pounds...)

When I walked in, the girl was staring off into space and someone had to point me out to her. After reading other reviews, this seems pretty normal at this location. I asked for the small size burrito while indicating the size with my hands cupped in half-moon shapes connected at the fingertips (same as the international symbol for "may I have a small side of ranch dressing"). The lady behind the counter and I went a couple of rounds of "we don't have smaller" and I thought she couldn't hear me because the music was so G.D. loud in there, and then I realized I am thinking of the Freebird's option (they have multiple sizes). So I was fine with their size. Not a big deal.

She asked me if I wanted beans and rice. I said black beans, no rice. So she pulls out the tortilla and I see her scoop up the rice and I said "no rice please, just beans." She evidently did not hear me from the loud-ass music they're playing in there as if to mask the fact that their service is lax, so I raised my voice and said "NO RICE!" My loudness and the context of what I said made me stop and think how ridiculous this place is. 

I went down the line and chose my fillers. She asked me if I wanted guacamole and mumbled something. I said, "yes, but what did you say?" She said there is an extra charge, thinking it's probably like 50 cents or something small. I said that's fine. At the cash register, the guy who'd pointed me out to the space cadet earlier rang up my total of $9.09. WTF? For a burrito and a soda? I found out that dollop of guacamole cost $1.50!!! I was like, "This place is ignorant!" I know, I know - I was the one paying for it, but I walked out thinking that I could buy an avocado for less and mash it up and put it in the burrito myself. A dollar fifty for guacamole is highway robbery if you ask me. Does your guacamole make me poo gold, Chipotle? I guess we'll have to wait and see. 

I am giving them an extra star because of their little story on the side of the soda cup about Wes Jackson and his revolutionary achievements in agriculture. I bet he gets his guac comp'd.
name: Chipotle Mexican Grill

text:
Sometimes it's hard to beat a big, tasty burrito.  I don't know who came up with the concept of the modern burrito, with rice, beans, cheese, specialty meats, and all the extra fixin's - but obviously, that person was a genius.

Since Chipotle burritos are custom made to your specs, let me give you my recommendation on the #1 best burrito that can be made from the ingredients Chipotle offers.  Here's what you tell the gal behind the counter (and yes, 19 times out of 20, it will be a gal, and she will be a recent immigrant.  Chipotle is kind of old school in this regard.)

-Burrito
-Rice
-Pinto Beans (for God's sake, trust me here, and deny that pesky black bean urge that you have.)
-Barbacoa (that's the Mexican style shredded bbq beef)
-Pico
-Sour Cream
-Cheese (you may have to ask for a touch extra)
Lettuce
Done!  That means no corn salsa, or any of that other silly junk.  

There you go.  That's a 100% Jonathan W. Approved and Guaranteed burrito, developed through years of experimentation.  Deviate from this formula at your own risk.

My take on the Chipotle concept:
-----------------------------------------------
Chipotle, as you know, is a chain, at one time affiliated with the dreaded McDonald's Corp., who has since divested its financial interest.   So if you hate McDonald's, rest assured that not one cent of Chipotle's profits go to the evil corporation.

Now, despite the fact that Chipotle is a chain, and that there are other specialty burrito chains, namely Freebirds and Q-doba, I feel that Chipotle offers a fairly unique product.  And they do so with remarkable consistency from location to location.  So, for better or worse, if you've been to one Chipotle - you've been to them all.  Which also means I will probably cut and paste the lion's share of this review for the many Chipotle locations I have visited, and intend to visit in the future.

text:
Gimmea free burrita, and I will bite. 

Along with it seems many other patrons in that evening, I took advantage of recent free burrito offer. I've managed to be a Chipotle virgin up to this point and figured this was the perfect time to reverse that. 

It takes about 3 Chipotle staff members on the assembly line to make this baby. Naturally raised chicken (+1 point), lime rice, black beans, a couple salsa choices (mild and a splash of hot for me), sour cream, white cheese. All nestled together warmly in a flour tortilla. I took my newborn home and unwrapped the swaddling (foil) and took a bite. Not too bad. Ok, onward... woah, woah, why so much rice?! And where is the flavor? Baby also had a cold cold heart of sour cream and cheese that did not manage to permeate the rest of the ingredients and remained a mass unto itself. It takes time and at least a little bit of care to make a good baby, this was more wham, bam, gracias ma'am, fare. 

Thank you for the sustenance and your pleasant staff, but I won't be back to pay next time.

text:
I'm happy to admit that I prefer my Mex in the style of Tex.  Since we're a far cry from the Lone Star State (Guero's & a Shiner Bock anyone?), and a further cry from the Pacific Time Zone where I first sampled Chipotle, I was beside myself with joy when I saw they were opening in Medford.  (Why Medford?  I got nothing against the Medfordese, but it just seems like an odd location to launch a franchise).  After moving back to Boston and having my friends rhapsodize about Anna's, I had resigned myself to the fact that my friends sucked.  White American Cheese product?  Anyway, I should save this tirade for a review of Annas.  We're here to discuss the sublime deliciousness that is Chipotle.  

Ahh, fresh cheese, all the ingredients in front of me, and, can you believe it?  Hot sauce that's actually HOT.  

I'm a creature of habit, and usually scarf down the fajita burrito.  I like not having beans forced upon me, but I do like the black bean option, in case I'm lacking fiber.

It's a party in there.  All the different tastes coming together, the cool sour cream, the spicy chicken.  I hope they open more of them in the area, so I don't have brave that crazy route 16/28/38/I-93 neighborhood anymore.

It's a lot of food, but you get what you pay for.  If I'm going to shell out 6 bucks for a burrito, I want it to fill me up.  All day.  Also, they've got three kinds of Tabasco sauce out in the open, waiting there, saying, "go ahead, make it even better!'  If you go with a friend be sure to try the guac. 

My one complaint, is that there are no additional japalenos to stick upon your creation.

In a city that lacks good burrito joints, it's totally worth the trip.
name: Chipotle Mexican Grill

text: I love Chipotle, and after moving to Medford, this became my new food joint by default. In all my years of eating Chipotle, this is the worst restaurant. I end up getting there at 6:25pm, and they hadn't even started my order. When they finally do, I watch the woman putting it together, and it's not even remotely close to what was on the order. So, I had to go down to the line, and walk them through the order since I guess they can't read orders well. Several other times going, the service is super slow, my burrito bowls are always half the size they should be (why are they always skimping on food, especially the meat??), and I get so much attitude from the employees. I don't get it. If I were you, I'd never order online for pickup at that location; you'll only get there to have your order not ready, or if it is, it's not at all done right (this has happened several times). Actually, I would go here at all. Pick another city - I promise you'll thank me.

text:
This is hands down the worst chipotle establishment I have been to in my life. Maybe even the worst fast-food establishment I've ever been too in general.

First time I went here, there were 3 people working. A tall gentleman, approximately 6'6" was clearly waiting for his food from a call-ahead order. 4-8 employees sat aimlessly in the back yelling to the gentleman, "yo dude how tall are you?". I don't know if they're all smoking dope or if the GM is just incredibly shitty at hiring.

I went back a 2nd time because I figured if the employees weren't all fired by now then the place wouldn't even still be open. I got in line with 4 people in front of me at a standstill, they were out of rice. We waited 10 minutes for the rice to come out as the line grew to ~15. I asked for white rice and it felt like I was in a soup kitchen. The rations were tiny because they now had to make orders for these 15 people. I then asked for pinto beans in which he loaded on black beans. I bit my tongue even as he then proceeded to add pinto beans. My jaw dropped at the incapacity to perform a simple task. I got to the register and asked for chips. To cap off the experience, they had no chips.

All in all, if you have any positions in Chipotle [CMG], I'm rating it a hard sell.

text:
I realize I am bringing down the average and I totally intend to update my review of Chipotle once I am able to actually try it. Until then, let me tell you why I'm giving them one star...

After a harrowing trail run in the Middlesex Fells reservation Saturday afternoon my boyfriend suggested "Let's try that burrito place you read about on Yelp that you want to try. Isn't it up here somewhere?"

Me, "Yes, it's in Medford but I don't know where exactly. I drove past it once. It might be route 16? I'll call and ask them where they are." After paying far too much money to call Dir. Assistance from a cell phone, I reach Chipotle:

Attempt 1: 
Chipotle worker: "Thank you for calling Chipotle"
Me: "Hi, can you please tell me where you are located?"
Chipotle worker: "Please hold."
Me: Patiently waited on hold for several minutes only to realize they disconnected me.

So, now we are now driving down 93 and I know that we're close to the exit where I think it is so I don't want to give up. I call again (after having to be reconnected by the Dir. Assistance operator).

Attempt 2: 
Same Chipotle worker(based on distinctive accent) : "Thank you for calling Chipotle" 
Me: "Hi, can you please tell me where you are located? We just got disconnected."
Chipotle worker: "Please hold."
Me: Waited on hold (a little less patiently) for several minutes only to realize they disconnected me again!

Okay, now I'm getting pissed! My boyfriend called the next time because I was too mad to deal with it. And now, on principal we had to find the damn place.  

Attempt 3: 
Same Chipotle worker (based on distinctive accent): "Thank you for calling Chipotle"
My boyfriend: "Hi, I need to know where you are located?"
Chipotle worker: "Please hold."
My boyfriend: "No, don't put me on hold. I just need to know your address and you have hung up on us twice."
Chipotle worker: "Please hold." 
My boyfriend: "I just need your address."
Chipotle worker: Finally, she asks someone in the background for the address and comes on the phone and says "Fellsway" and hangs up.

We are now aggravated beyond belief. So, my boyfriend while driving looks to his left and wouldn't you know...there was Chipotle. After all that, we found it on our own anyway.

So, we went in and the line was approx. 30 people deep, and I am not exaggerating. It might have moved fast but we didn't wait to find out. We were so put off by the whole phone experience and now this line. So, we walked next door to Boston Market. 

Believe it or not, I would still like to try Chipotle.
name: Chipotle Mexican Grill
Ambience: {'romantic': False, 'intimate': False, 'touristy': False, 'hipster': False, 'divey': False, 'classy': False, 'trendy': False, 'upscale': False, 'casual': True}

text:
Food taste is good. Service and take out is HORRENDOUS. By all means DO NOT do delivery from this place. You will get half portion of a meal.

Due to the covid19, I have been doing delivery as my main source of takeout. However, I feel like this location should strongly remove delivery as an option. I gave them 2 chances after my first incident and both times has been the same thing. My order is always the same: burrito bowl x2, 1 brown rice/1 white rice, 1 side order of quac (not on the bowl), and both contains carnitas/sour cream/cheese/lettuce/corn/salsa. each time there was barely any rice, the portion was half of the container and didn't even reach the top of the brown bowl, they also had one bowl with little (but I'd take it) lettuce, and the other bowl had literally 5 pieces of the shredded lettuce. 

What I do not understand is that, chipotle has a system of one specific person doing certain things. How is it that one person is making two of the almost exact bowl end up having a product that doesn't even look alike. Especially going to the same customer!!! I'm so disappointed and think management should either watch over their staff or should just remove the delivery option.

text:
This is hands down the worst chipotle establishment I have been to in my life. Maybe even the worst fast-food establishment I've ever been too in general.

First time I went here, there were 3 people working. A tall gentleman, approximately 6'6" was clearly waiting for his food from a call-ahead order. 4-8 employees sat aimlessly in the back yelling to the gentleman, "yo dude how tall are you?". I don't know if they're all smoking dope or if the GM is just incredibly shitty at hiring.

I went back a 2nd time because I figured if the employees weren't all fired by now then the place wouldn't even still be open. I got in line with 4 people in front of me at a standstill, they were out of rice. We waited 10 minutes for the rice to come out as the line grew to ~15. I asked for white rice and it felt like I was in a soup kitchen. The rations were tiny because they now had to make orders for these 15 people. I then asked for pinto beans in which he loaded on black beans. I bit my tongue even as he then proceeded to add pinto beans. My jaw dropped at the incapacity to perform a simple task. I got to the register and asked for chips. To cap off the experience, they had no chips.

All in all, if you have any positions in Chipotle [CMG], I'm rating it a hard sell. Short it now.

text: Flavor is still good but the value gets worse every time I go there. It seems that over the last couple of years that they skimp on the quantity of food they serve. I'm not saying that I need a lot of food, but their meet portions have gone down by close to 50% since this time last year. I just received an order via Door Dash and it had 1/3 of the bowl empty. This has become their new norm. When I complained last time the manager said, "Some of our new people don't always give you the amount that they are supposed to." I think it's more likely that the local management or corporate mentality is that if they give us less over a long enough period of time, we won't notice, thereby boosting their profitability. text:
2017 update: Sadly, this location has not improved at all in the last two years. Serving sizes are not consistent. Today, I ordered a bowl for pick up, got home and found that it didn't even fill up half of the bowl which everyone knows is not normal. The flavor and quality of the food is getting significantly worse. The only plus side is the current employees are friendly and they finally fixed the giant pot hole in the parking lot. The only lesson I've learned from eating at this location is to order on the app and pick up in store because long lines are the norm at this store. 

----

This location is often one of the worst Chipotle's I've been to. Granted, I live in the area, so it's the most convenient to get to so sometimes I hope to god that the next experience will be better than the last. It hardly ever is. They're VERY slow and considering there's only about five places for people to get lunch in the area, you'd think they'd be a bit faster. The food quality isn't completely terrible - when chicken still looks and tastes like chicken, I can't complain too much. 

HOWEVER, what I can complain about is the sanitation issues this location has. Firstly, this location always has very dirty work stations. The employees are not careful about keeping the worktop clear of food. But the worst part is that they contaminate food because of their lack of sanitation. 

My roommate is vegan - chipotle is one of the few vegan/vegetarian friendly "fast food" places and one of the ONLY vegan friendly restaurants in New Albany. Every single time we go to this location, there is cheese in the guacamole. Granted, it's corporate's fault for thinking that it's a good idea to put cheese right next to guac, but the employees here truly must not care about accidentally mixing cheese into their vegan guacamole. The last few times my roommage and I have eaten at this location, he skipped the guac altogether because he can't trust it anymore. This is sad because when you get veggies, you get free guac and he LOVES Chipotle's guac. 

But the ending point is that this location is dirty. You can't trust this location to have a clean workstation and you can't trust that there isn't cheese in the guacamole - vegans beware.
name: Chipotle Mexican Grill

text:
I'm not sure if they are understaffed or don't know how to properly schedule associates, but every time I come in as a DoorDash driver, I'm waiting between 15-45 minutes for the order after the pick up time. It's not the staff's fault by any means and this falls on management for not having a team prepared for the massive amount of orders. I highly suggest management explores the option of turning off DoorDash during peak times to reduce the wait time, guest aggravation, and most importantly, to help the staff out. They're probably stressed and overwhelmed and they will get burnt out, leading to unhappy employees and a high turnover rate. I say this as someone who has been a manager in the service industry. 

I also want to add that there were so many customers who were waiting for their mobile orders standing in the restaurant that there was practically no social distancing. I have never seen so many angry people in one restaurant.
name: Chipotle Mexican Grill

text: So I have ordered lunch from this Chipotle twice this month and , well , was slightly disappointed. The food wasn't bad and my order was correct but the portions were not up to snuff. I have eaten dine in here a couple of times and I have had to ask for a little more rice and cheese at the counter but my online delivery order was tiny, it barely covered the bottom of the bowl. This was the case for both orders, and frankly for what you pay for a burrito bowl I would expect to at least have a lot of rice, but it was weird because I was able to actually finish the bowl and eat chips and guacamole. Dining in I can't finish a bowl in one sitting but for take out my bowl was a sad empty place. My solution was get double rice and double meat, the cost was 3$ more but finally I was full with just the burrito bowl. The free delivery softened the extra meat price.

text:
I attempted to get a quick bite on my way home.
I knew this was a bad idea soon as I walked in. The staff was chatting a lot to each other.
I was greeted by what seemed like the only employee wanting to do their job. From then on, I was informed they were out of chicken and I could wait if I wanted. I ended up switching to steak because I was tired of waiting after a few minutes. The bowl wasn't anything special and tasted decent. Nervous because it seems like Chipotle has a good scare every other week somewhere and with the staff half paying attention it wouldn't surprise me if it happened here.

Lastly, the guacamole had an upcharge of roughly 30%.
It cost about $6/7 for the steak bowl and it cost over $2 for guacamole. I've been in the restaurant industry and understand an up charge for guacamole. Most places charge 50 cents to $1, but over $2 for the menial guac I received is insane. Poor service and ridiculous pricing is how you drive away customers. ‍

text:
I will preface this by saying my Chipotle of choice, Medford, MA, sets the bar absurdly high. From the friendly staff, to the overstuffed burrito, oozing goodness it would be hard to find another 'rito Mecca that can compete. I didn't think that when Medford climbed out of the pool that the Watertown, MA would drop the ball like Ryan Lochte, leaving me shaking my head as to how? Medford gave you the lead, Watertown you were supposed to be my anchor. You could have taken that lead and swam with it, instead you sunk. 

The staff was very friendly, so kudos there, guys. The perfect 'rito - it all begins with rice. It's like the soft down pillow for my head of chicken. This pillow was missing some feathers. I'm just saying, the 'le never disappointed before on the pillow and this one was like a beaten down, flat wisp where wonderful fluff once was. I'm not a bean man, so none of that. On to the head of chicken, or lack thereof. I just want a spoonful, not a lot to ask for. What I got was the shimmy. Yup, guys, the scoop and shake leaving me licking my lips wishing for more. Not double chicken, I don't want a Siamese twin, just a fully formed head not one that looks like a hammer cracked it.Next those wonderful toppings, the sheets of the 'rito. Great job Watertown on the salsa and corn, you know what, not too bad on the sour cream either. But wait, what's a 'rito without cheese? Nothing worth eating, that's what. I'm not saying I Rain Manned it but I'm talking like 11 shreds. I had to ask for more! At least they don't charge me extra for that. Don't do it, 'le. Just don't don't. It'd break my heart. What about the comforter you might ask? That tasty, warm tortilla. It had a HOLE, in it. Letting all the heat escape, letting my 'rito collapse. Not cool, guys.

 All in all, Watertown, you let me down. Medford is totally Michael Phelps in this analogy. So, please step it up. I'm a little disappointed.

text: Ever since I discovered Chipotle a few years ago I've been going there at least once a month.  It's such a great fresh and healthy alternative to most of the other quick service meal options out there.  I usually get the bowl which is basically a burrito with no tortilla, served in a bowl.  They have chicken, beef, carnitas, and barbacoa, although I usually stick to the chicken.  The flavor there is unique and quite good.  Like some other people have said, the portions can vary depending on who makes your meal for you, but I usually leave with leftovers so it always works for me.  The one drawback about Chipotle is that their flavor is so unique, it gets old after a while.  If you tend to go once a week because you work nearby, you may get sick of it soon.  But, I suppose that could be true of just about anyplace.  I definitely recommend Chipotle for their quick, healthy, reasonably priced meals.

text:
I may be a snobby foodie sometimes, but I'm also a fan of quick on-the-go eats.  American culture at it's finest? Say hello to Chipotle.

First off, don't ever call this Mexican food. It's not. Don't even get me started. Tex-Mex? Maybe.

This Chipotle in Watertown is my favorite location to visit. They are often crowded at lunchtime, since it's 1) connected to a mall with a withering food court, 2) central to several office parks, and 3) it's one of maybe three delicious options in the walkable area.

I have yet to find this place dirty. I'm also quite the stickler for food-handling safety and I've never once seen these guys mess up. I cannot say the same for other locations (I'm looking at you, Needham St in Newton). And the staff is incredibly friendly! I'm only a semi-regular here, but I do get my fair share of smiles from the staff and plenty of toppings as my burrito bowl works its way down the line.

I'm a firm believer in this Watertown location for sure.

text: I strongly advise against the Chipotle branch. As other guests reported, there is a nasty and angry  food server who treats customers horribly. He is a black guy about 40 years old with a short beard. He still works there after all these reviews! I was there on Saturday October 1st at 6:30pm with my wife and son. There were 10 people in the line but it took 15 minutes to get to the servers. My wife told the black guy with the beard she wanted half chicken half barbaqua. His response was "I couldn't understand a word you said. I would give you whatever you ask If I could only hear you". I repeated what my wife said loudly "she wants half chicken half barbaqua". He looked at me but didn't respond, then looked back at my wife and had her repeat at least 2 times each item. He then looked at me without saying anything. I told him I wanted half chicken half barbaqua bowl. He did the same to me. My son stood to my left and next in line but this worker  looked past my son's head and yelled to a person that wasn't even at the counter but back in the line and asked him what he wanted. That person pointed to my son. This worker looked at my son with a very angry face and didn't say a word just stared at him and banged his large food serving  spoon on the metal food container. My son said he wanted half chicken half beef plate. The worker asked him several times about each item then he looked at me and then back at my son he took 4 pieces of chicken and 6 pieces of beef and put them in my sons plate and moved on to the next customer. More meat?" my son said "yes, can you put more meat please" the worker said "do you want double portion? text:

text:
I absolutely love chipotle and have probably to almost every location in Orlando.  My first date was at one.  I go to Chipotle whenever I can.   That being said, this may be one of the worst restaurants I've ever been in.  First off, parking is horrible and confusing.  That should have been enough to warn me away.  Second the employees are unfriendly and anything they said to me was mumbled I could barely hear them.  Third, the food was unevenly cooked--there was a practically raw onion in my so limp they should be overcooked spaghetti fajita mix, and red bits in my carnitas--and not really up to the standards of other chipotle locations.  But worst of all--as a former server--was the fact that I saw three different employees cross contaminate food on the line.  One spilled steak on the counter and threw it back in with the rest, another one spilled the serving utensil from the steak into the carnitas and reused it, and then the third kept spilling lettuce and guacamole into the cheese.  I was horrified because that means anyone with food sensitivities who ate here could get sick!  Luckily I don't but I'm still pretty picky with what I eat so that's still bad for me.  I understand being in a rush but it wasn't even that busy!  I couldn't even finish my burrito because of it, what a waste.

Just talked to the manager and she had no idea it was happening but said she would get to the bottom of it and said that it shouldn't have been happening.  I hope she does because she's right it shouldn't have been.
name: Chipotle Mexican Grill

text:
One word: barbacoa!!!!!!!!

My favorite thing about this chain is that they are extremely open about what products you're actually putting into your body. As someone who aims to cook at home 90% of the time, it is important to me knowing that they receive their meat on a regular basis and prep everything daily. That way I can feel less guilty; always a plus!

I ordered their salad with barbacoa and all the fixings, and got an order of guacamole on the side. I found that I get more guac if I order it on the side and they cram it into their to-go cups. It came out to just shy of $10 per person, without a drink. I didn't use their dressing; it was far too tangy and sugary for me to put on my salad. Luckily, the meat had enough juice and flavor to compensate the mediocrity that salad usually brings to the table.
