text:
I haven't been to this location as many times as I have the one on Lake Mary Blvd. and the one on 436 in Altamonte Springs, but it still does the trick for me when I get that Chipotle craving. I was here last week and the vegetarian burrito I ordered really hit the spot. I think that my most recent visit to this store was the fastest and most convenient one I've had at ANY location. I was in and out of the store with my precious burrito in what I'm now guessing was under 3 minutes. I was surprised! I probably would've spent more time in a drive-thru lane, and even before ordering at one, than I spent in here the other day. Not that I was in a hurry or anything when I was here ... I just couldn't believe how effortless this recent visit was!

I only have an issue with one thing about this location: the parking/accessibility. As far as I can tell, there's really only one decent way to get into the store's parking lot, and that's from 17-92 and coming from the direction of Lee Rd. I was on Fairbanks when I was trying to get here last week and decided to turn into the parking lot of a bank or office building (I can't remember what it is) to see if it connects to the Chipotle parking lot. (Fortunately, it does.) If I hadn't turned there, I would've had to go to the traffic light at Fairbanks/17-92, go onto 17-92 and perhaps make a U-turn and head back toward Fairbanks. I don't know ... hard to explain unless you've been to this place before and know what I mean. Not a big deal. I'll still rate my experiences and the food I've had from here very highly. Four stars.
name: Chipotle Mexican Grill

text:
I've never been a big fan of burritos, but when I am craving one, I try to get it from Chipotle because I really like the taste of it. I like the beef that they have and the spiciest salsa is actually spicy. I'm tired of other places where the salsa barely does anything to me. I also like that they make it in front of you so you can pick and choose what you like to put on there.

The only qualm I have about it is the fact that the tables are not movable. Or maybe only the tables in the booths are not movable. I'm not sure. But we went with a big group one time and we ended up having to sit separately because we couldn't gather the tables together. That was really "un-smart" in my opinion. I don't see the sense in screwing in the tables.

Parking can also be a hassle during the rush lunch hour. They have a tiny, little lot that gets full real easily, and parking on the street can be busy too with the other businesses around.

But aside from that, I really like Chipotle and what they have to offer.

text:
If I were rating Chipotle not by location but as a franchise in general, I would rate them 5-stars. They are the MOST consistent chain restaurant in the country. So much so, that I installed the Chipotle App on my GPS unit so that ANYTIME, ANYWHERE in the country, I can find out if I'm near one. Now THAT'S obsession.

After visiting the Winter Park location twice, it is absolutely evident to me that Floridians are also OBSESSED with Chipotle and more locations need to be built in the Orlando area. It is simply not prudent to leave your office at 11:50, go to Chipotle, wait on line for 25-35 minutes, and not get back to the office until 1:25 PM.

A googlemaps search shows that there are NINE Chipotles in the Orlando metro area. Jeez, maybe you guys need a Q-Doba or four, or something. But seriously, things need to get sped up here, either by another area franchise or by efficiency training (which I don't think can help, they move pretty fast here) or I won't be able to go back.

Also the parking sucks ass. There's like 7 spots, otherwise you need to park on this random side street or in an office park which clearly tells you not to park there.

The food was just as good as any other Chipotle in the United States.

And did someone complain about lack of drinks? Seriously? Try going to 99% of fast food chain places, where all you have is Pepsi, 7-Up, Dew, Barqs and some acidic-carbonated lemonade. Chipotle has TONS more options in the glass case behind the counter, Snapple, Arizona, bottled water, etc. Oh yeah, AND BEER. And fresh brewed sweetened and unsweetened iced-tea by the fountains. Sorry, that is simply not a valid complaint.
name: Chipotle Mexican Grill

text:
This Chipotle has been about evenly 50/50 hit or miss for me. Which sucks because I love me some Chipotle- I have a Pavlovian response whenever someone mentions a veggie bowl so I've been to several locations.

They have always been friendly at this location, so my 3 stars have nothing to do with poor customer service or a dirty restaurant. It has to do with the food.

Now I've worked food service, so I understand rushes. But I think most customers would agree that waiting a couple of minutes for top quality food is worth it. Today's veggie bowl had "sauteed" veggies that were basically raw because they were clearly rushing to just get the veggies out. The rice, which normally is crack to me (mmm cilantro and lime flavor) was very bland and clumps of it were stuck together so there was clearly no flavor in the center of the clumps.

It's a shame they can't be consistent with their food during rushes. I've definitely had great meals from this location but I've also had very disappointing, bland meals on the regular. I hope the managers can figure out how to manage the food quality during a rush in the future. For now I'll stick to the other restaurants around the area during my lunch breaks.

text: I'm an avid fan of Chipotle, but this particular location needs some serious improvements. There were six people pushing my burrito bowl along (perhaps that's why I couldn't park in the parking lot...employees have taken all the spots), and five of the six were extremely chincy on the toppings. (I'm guessing it would have been six of six had the sixth individual actually served any food.) Twice I asked for "just a little more" veggies or black beans (two different individuals addressed my requests, mind you), only to get an eye roll and a blatantly obvious attempt to give as little of the said ingredient as possible. I've complained to other stores in the past when such behavior occurs, and Chipotle explained that they have no problem giving you more of any ingredient when you ask (except meat and guac, for which they must charge an additional fee -- totally understandable). Yet I can't help but feel like the trainers at this store drilled it home to give as little as possible. By the time I got to the cheese, I was too annoyed to even bother asking for more, having been practically ignored by my first two requests. The woman working the cheese station seriously grabbed about a quarter of what I'm used to seeing at other Chipotle restaurants. I'll never return to this restaurant again.

text:
So, I thought it was a good time to be over the big Chipotle scare, but I may have thought too soon.  I went to the Winter Park Chipotle and was greeted by a guy that seemed very distracted.  Nobody was behind me in line, and nobody was working the toppings station, so once he was done with his part, he just left my burrito there to wait.  Way to not go the extra mile, dude.  So my burrito and I waited for the next person to return to her station.  Once there, she added the toppings I asked for, but seemed annoyed when I asked her to mix my burrito innards up...because most people want a full on globby bite of guacamole, isn't that why we pay extra?  So she grabbed a fork, mushed the guac blob around like a child that doesn't want to eat their veggies, and was done...so there was that.  I kinda laughed and she got even more annoyed, so she half folded my burrito (don't they have burrito folding degrees here?)...then didn't even completely wrap my burrito with the foil and laid it on the counter to be invaded by whatever germs have jumped on the counter from the passing of payment.  Awesome.  Nobody was at the register, so I grabbed a bag in an effort to beat the 5 second rule by bagging my own food, when I realized the bag only had 1 handle.  Huh?  I finally got to one with 2 handles when the cashier returned to the counter (from sweeping the floors, full on grabbing the dust pan and everything) and reached for my food to bag it for me.  I quickly said, I got it, you've been sweeping!  He got the idea and went to wash his hands and another lady completed ringing me up.  This was the grossest visit I've ever had at Chipotle, but I'm giving it 3 stars because I did maul that burrito and guacamole, so I feel like the cooks in the back deserve 3 stars for taste.  

Hopefully, Chipotle will get back to the on point-ness that I once loved them for, but it seems like morale could use a boost here, and maybe a refresher in cleanliness....??
name: Chipotle Mexican Grill

text: My husband and I stopped there on Sunday night after Christmas shopping. The woman that waited on me was pleasant and accommodating, as I have a gluten allergy. As we moved along the station to select items it was clear that the food was becoming dry and needed to be attended to. We turned to take a seat and all the tabletops were dirty. I asked the man at the register if I could have a rag to wash off a table and he happily came and wiped off one table and returned to the register. There weren't any new customers at this point. I looked around and the dining room was totally filthy with food and other items on the floor, dirty seats, empty napkin holders, and a sticky floor near the soda machine. I asked a woman on break if the manager was in. She got her for me. I said to her, "Look around this place. What do you see? This place is filthy! With all the health complaints with Chipotle lately, I would think you would care about this." I've never done this before in my 64 years of life but I truly was aghast. She said she was dealing with an employee problem and that she took total responsibility. Meanwhile she did not direct her staff to wash tables or sweep the floor. She eventually walked out herself and refilled the napkin holder. The woman taking her break heard me talking to my husband and asked the guy at the register to wash some tables and sweep. He tried, but was clueless about how to clean a table, wipe down the benches, or sweep properly. It was obvious that staff training in this restaurant is poor. Not one staff member saw it as there responsibility to clean up during downtime. I love the food, but it makes me uncomfortable about the quality of preparation when the dining room itself is so filthy and the management is not doing its job by giving direction or making sure staff is properly trained. All it takes is showing what is expected and making sure that staff support one another by keeping the place clean. I don't expect to go back to this location.
name: Chipotle Mexican Grill
Ambience: {'touristy': False, 'hipster': False, 'romantic': False, 'divey': False, 'intimate': False, 'trendy': False, 'upscale': False, 'classy': False, 'casual': False}

text: I placed an order for pick up through the Chipotle App. When I arrived at the restaurant to pick up my order, the server could not find it. After providing both my email confirmation and the App's confirmation, the server then informed me that "Someone had stolen my order." This of course both confused and infuriated me! How could this have happened? The server then began remaking my order but did so very carelessly and rushed through it sloppily! At this point, he even stated that the person who "stole" my order did so without having a confirmation for it! What type of pick up policy does Chipotle have where anybody can just walk in and pick up food without providing proof of purchase?! It's clear that the staff just gave my order away without a second thought. When I finally peered into my to go bag, I found a half-thrown together burrito bowl that is half the normal portion size along with a half-rolled burrito barely covered with aluminum foil! I am highly disappointed and dissatisfied with this service to the point where I will never visit this Chipotle location again. I strongly encourage Chipotle to develop better standards of validating identities for pick up orders!

text:
This is my first time going to this location, as it wasn't there when I lived here before. I work not too far away and it was an easy drive for my lunch break.

The setup is similar to every other Chipotle, and the menu offerings are the same. If for some reason you've never been in your reading my review, it's cafeteria-style where you walk up and pick what you want, whether Bowl, Taco, Burrito... You get the idea. From there, you pick your protein or tofu, then you pick your toppings. You have four different sauces to choose from, different kinds of beans, rice, lettuce, and cheese to choose from.

The time that I went the service was super fast even though it was lunch time. The staff were friendly and I got in and out pretty quickly. It seems to be a pretty popular location with all that the Millenia area has to offer nearby. That also means that traffic is a nightmare as that area is not well designed for travel.

text:
Finally had the time to write this review so here I go. Let me preface everything I'm about to say by emphasizing the fact that I used to frequent this location quite a lot. I live by Millenia and it's filled with franchises, so I've always opted for Chipotle seeing as it's not so terrible for you. 

However, after the absolutely horrible experience I had this weekend, I can confidently say I will NEVER return to any of the locations...ever. On Saturday, I ordered a veggie bowl to go and took it home. Mid-bowl, I chewed on something really strange. As I retrieved it from my mouth, I noticed it looked an awful lot like a fingernail. I have 10 fingers, each with a nail and I cut them frequently, so I know what they look like. Still, I double checked before making a decision. I got a second opinion from my mom who was with me and she was horrified when she saw it. I then took it upon myself to compare it to an uncooked grain of whole wheat rice to see if maybe that was what it was. It definitely had no resemblance, and after conducting this analysis, I came to the sound conclusion that it was indeed a fingernail. 

Ok. So next step, call the restaurant and let them know the inconvenience you've encountered in the hopes they will help...right? Wrong. When I called, the manager came on the phone and immediately seemed annoyed with me as if I was the one who had just served him a fingernail fiesta for dinner. He first said he would give me my money back, and began to look my order up in the system. He asked what I got and I answered - a veggie bowl with chips and guac. He responded with, "okay so it was about 7 something?" I said it was about 11. He then, in an aggravated manner, told me guac wasn't included in a veggie bowl to which I answered, "yes, but I got extra guac." He was acting as if I was trying to get a free meal which was already annoying me. Like dude, I just got a fingernail in my food. I'm not some weirdo who goes around claiming I have fingernails in my food for free rides. 

ANYWAY...he then said it was impossible that it was a fingernail because all of his employees have to wear gloves....as if no employee ever in the history of food service has ever broken protocol. Nice try. 

At this point, he doesn't even want to return my money back and asks that I come show him the fingernail. I cannot lie...I am AGGRAVATED at this point but after a much heated conversation, I say alright...if you're really looking for a scandal. I was so so upset by this that in my frantic preparation to go, I lost the damn fingernail. I looked for the fingernail on my hands and knees with a flashlight for 15 minutes, understanding how entirely ridiculous the situation was. As my mom laughed through my fingernail search, tears came down my face as I yelled in frustration, "IT'S NOT FUNNY!" It kind of was. I can now see the humor in the situation, but was definitely not happy at all as it was occurring.

I gave up, ultimately realizing I wasn't going to find it, but was so upset by the situation, I felt I needed to write this very long review to address the lack of professionalism on the manager's part. Regardless of whether the finger nail was there or not (it was), you never deal with a customer in the way that I was dealt with, especially given the situation. I am now grossed out by both the food here and the manager. 

I understand this review is absurdly long and many may not take the time to read it, but if you don't just...EAT HERE WITH CAUTION.
name: Chipotle Mexican Grill
Ambience: {'touristy': False, 'hipster': False, 'romantic': False, 'divey': False, 'intimate': False, 'trendy': False, 'upscale': False, 'classy': False, 'casual': True}

text:
So used to be a 5-star location. My family goes here frequently as we live just around the corner. Last three visits were disappointing. I don't think I will be going here again. Somethings that went down in the last three visits (in no particular order). 1) Came late at night with my little daughter. Parked but saw that a lot of the chairs were being put up inside restaurant. Not wanting to unbuckle the kid only to find out that the restaurant had already closed, I rolled down window and asked two employees sitting in outside dining area of the restaurant if they had already closed. They both looked at me, then at each other, and rolled their eyes. 
2) They "ran out" of guac. I buy only veggie bowls so the guac is my "meat". It comes with that type of bowl. I still had to pay full price for my bowl. Oh well.., it still tasted ok. 
3) Certain employees are very stingy with the ingredients. I mean.., I know it is an approximation and an art form.., but come on! They act like it's money from their retirement fund or something. Tiny little pile of three-corns in the middle of the bowl. My veggie bowl should be a VEGGIE bowl! That IS the focus!
4) Out of guac again. Do they not have a manager that is supposed to calculate amount of product needed!!???

text:
I've been here quiet a few times to finally give it a verdict of one word: exhausting...

I understand since this is probably the only chipotle in Grandview area every single 20 something-year-old hits this place at some point of the day so the line is always stretching out to the door which is good news for chipotle ... hey! your sales numbers are pretty good over here.. but that's where the buck stops.

As if the parking is not awkward enough you still have those douchebags insisting on trying to park their gigantic F250 trucks in a parking lot that was designed to fit 8 to 10 Toyota Corolla's on a good day.

 Don't get me started on the soccer moms with their minivans stuck on reverse frantically trying to back out of the parking spot. It is like a horror movie... Final destination part 7.

The staff here are expectedly not overly friendly. I don't expect them to be friendly . After all it's a busy assembly line . I get it .. but I don't understand the rudeness and the way some of them slap the toppings on the bowl , you would think you are the in the prison food line... I mean come on. Be gentle on splashing the heck out of that sour cream. That poor salsa verde hasn't done anything to you to beat it like that. 

There is absolutely no excuse for food bits to be flying around and splattered all over around the food trays. Very sloppy.

Can you please not scrap the very last bit of the fajita then pass the bowl, only to swap the empty tray with a full fresh one right infront of my eyes?. What have I done to deserve that?.  That loud scrapping noise... please, I don't need bits of scrapped Trey material in my food.

text:
You know how in the 90s everyone was predicting that we would have flying cars and other unique, futuristic methods of transportation. Well, it seems that the designers of this location were sold on this idea in full. Certainly, this location could not have been designed with regular cars in mind as there are probably a total 10 parking spots available. This makes for a very frustrating time trying to get your burrito fix. 

When it comes to the food, this location has usually been excellent for me. One of the most inconsistent food items available are fajitas and coincidentally, these are my favorite part of my bowl. The short north location often has mushy or burnt fajitas, but that's not the case here. The steak has also been consistently free of fatty bits, something that sloppier locations tend to ignore. So in a nutshell, excellent food here. 

Service is hit or miss. Sometimes attentive and quick. Sometimes a bit slow. Around dinner and lunch time, this place gets really hopping, so if you're looking to avoid a crowd, I'd suggest coming at a different time. 

Tl;dr - if we could teleport, this place would be 5 stars.

text:
I am someone that enjoys writing positive reviews! But I am fed up with the service at this location. I've been going to this location for over 10 years. In the past when I thought of Chipotle this was my favorite location but this last visit has ended that relationship. The employees have they have recently hired do not treat me like valued customer. They are snappy and short with me every time. 

The last three times I have been there they have failed at completing my order. First, I wanted to complete my order with a coke, paid, then was told the entire fountain machine was out of order. A normal Chipotle would refund me or give me a coupon. Not this one. They just told me it was out of order. 

Second visit, I ask for guacamole and they tell be there out and I can wait 10-15 minutes if I want for them to make more guacamole. How does this happened? 

This last visit I ordered a burrito and tacos. Paid for both and left. After getting home I realize they never put the tacos in my bag. So, I drive back and ask them for my tacos. The cash register says,"oh, so you're the one that left your tacos". Thinking in my head "no that was you"  while he hands me the cold tacos sitting off to the side with no apology. 

All three times, the same employees were working. I go to Chipotle for a healthy and convenient meal but the last three times have been very irritating. I will have to go to Qdoba down the street or drive further to a different Chipotle next time. I will not be going back to that location till something changes with the management.
name: Chipotle Mexican Grill

text:
Not really worth a visit to this location in my opinion. I never thought to check reviews for a chipotle before, but the bad reviews for this place just go on and on. 

The parking is atrocious as others have stated. That's already annoying enough to deter me from going during peak hours. 

Even when I go during off hours at like 3:45pm and I can get a parking spot, there are still other major issues. Why can't I just grab my own online order? Waiting and staring at it while the cashier keeps ringing up other people is frustrating. Besides that, they don't seem to be able to keep promise times. The other day I saw about 10 people standing outside? 

The last straw for me today was ordering a sofritas bowl that was filled with chicken and steak. Not just one piece, but MULTIPLE! I am not a vegetarian but I was still unsure what I was even actually eating. The bowl was overfilled too and soggy on the bottom. 

Reminds me of another time a few months ago when the black bean juice was so much and it spilled all in my car because the lid wasn't on tight. I am just over this place. Doesn't feel very cleanly and not worth it. Try Bibibop or something else instead.

text:
"How can someone possibly give a Chipotle two stars?!" you might ask. This specific location on 5th Ave in Grandview has two major issues:

1) Parking - The parking lot is tiny and narrow, which makes it difficult to navigate. Especially with cars pulling in and out constantly. 

2) The service - The employees here are usually unfriendly and very slow. This causes a ridiculously long line to form - usually from at least the cash register to the door and sometimes winding among the tables as well. They also are often out of ingredients (usually the fajita vegetables), which causes additional slowdown as people wait for the food to be cooked.

One tip to avoid the line - order online! From my experience, they seem to prioritize online orders over the people who are ordering in the store.

All that being said, the food itself tastes the same as any other Chipotle. It just isn't worth the effort to get it.

text:
Pad your pickup time with ~10 minutes. 
We've ordered here many times during the pandemic and have always had correct orders, but actually picking up your food is really difficult. 
At peak times the parking lot is far too small and is a flurry of activity. You'll catch many people (myself included) making loops through the lot to the nearby intersection as a way of waiting for a parking spot to open up. Once inside it's usually packed with people waiting for orders well past their pickup time; I waited 20 minutes beyond my pickup time last visit and finally received my meal, which was cold.
I absolutely appreciate that you can tell the staff is working hard to fill the high number of orders they're receiving, and they're really good at keeping track of who is there for pickups. I would just recommend making sure you're not in a rush if you order from here for dinner.
name: Chipotle Mexican Grill

text: The food is always fine for me here, but this place has no idea how to adapt to a covid world. Social distancing falls apart as soon as you walk in. I think most of this is a faulty takeout order system. I think it's promising unrealistic pickup times, which results in the customer waiting approx 20min past their pickup time. Pre-pandemic, that's a minor problem. But today, your whole reason for ordering pickup was to avoid a zoo of people. Next thing you know, you're standing in the middle of one, like being at Walmart.
